## Detection Architecture (Post-Integration)

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Input Frame] --> B[M1 Scene Classifier]
    A --> C[YOLO Vehicle Detection]
    A --> D[YOLO Pose Detection]
    
    B -->|cls_conf| E{Pre-filter}
    E -->|cls_conf < 0.20| F[No Accident]
    E -->|cls_conf >= 0.20| G[Geometric Analysis]
    
    C --> G
    D --> G
    
    G --> H[Vehicle-Vehicle Scoring]
    G --> I[Vehicle-Pedestrian]
    
    C --> J[M2 Damage Classifier]
    
    H --> K{Any Detection?}
    I --> K
    
    K -->|Yes| L[Ensemble Fusion]
    K -->|No| M{Fallback Paths}
    
    M --> N[5e: Single Vehicle + M1]
    M --> O[5f: VP + M1]
    M --> P[5g: Damage + M1 ≥40%]
    M --> Q[5g-ii: Damage >90% + M1 ≥20%]
    M --> R[5h: Scene-only M1 ≥85%]
    
    J --> L
    B --> L
    
    L --> S[Fused Confidence]
    S --> T[Report + Annotated Frame]
```

## Key Design Decisions

1. **Stage 5g-ii threshold (M2 > 90%)**: Very high M2 confidence is strong enough evidence even without M1 agreement. This is a deliberate asymmetry — M2 analyzes actual vehicle crops, so its high-confidence predictions are more specific than M1's scene-level assessment.

2. **Ensemble weights (40/35/25)**: Geometric analysis gets the highest weight because it provides the most specific evidence (actual physical overlap). M1 gets more than M2 because it analyzes the full scene context. M2 gets the least because damage alone doesn't prove an accident just happened (could be pre-existing).

3. **Scene-only detection (Stage 5h)**: Only triggers when M1 ≥ 85% AND zero vehicles detected. This prevents false positives in normal scenes while catching smoke/debris-obscured crashes.
